Description    
	Sodium is the sixth most abundant element in the Earth's crust and
 exists in numerous minerals such as feldspars, sodalite and rock salt(NaCl).
It is a soft and silvery-white element. It is highly reactive metal and is 
never found free in nature. Sodium is an alkali metal. It is too much active 
element. It always occurs as apart of a compound. The most common source of 
sodium in the Earth is Halite. Halite is nearly pure sodium chloride (NaCl).
It is also called rock salt.          